	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Where would you store the extra attribute information?</div><br />Same place <em>Gauntlet</em>, <em>Rad Racer II</em>, and <em>Napoleon Senki</em> store their extra nametable data: on a RAM in the cartridge.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">Drag wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">At this point, the only reason for using a &quot;lesser&quot; mapper (or no mapper) is if you want the challenge.</div><br />I imagine that in a mockup thread, known ways of bending hardware limits (such as MMC5 ExGrafix) are fair game because copyright takes away the need to optimize your mockup for actually being able to reproduce it. But it becomes important if you want to reuse the overall art style of your mockup (especially its way of conforming to hardware limits) in an original game that you plan to sell on cartridge.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
